th German, Dutch, Danish, and Norwegian: topographic name for someone who lived in or by a small wood, from Middle English, Middle Low German, Danish, and Norwegian <i>holt</i>, or a habitational name from one of the many places called with this word. In England, the surname is widely distributed, but more common in Lancashire and Yorkshire than elsewhere."],"variants":[{"name":"Hohlt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Ordell.","North German: variant of   Holt   with the additional <i>h</i> reflecting the lengthened vowel or a variant of   Hohl   with the addition of excrescent <i>-t</i>.","Scandinavian: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holten","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Nils.","Dutch (also <b>Van Holten</b>) and North German: habitational name from any of the places so called, from Low German <i>holt</i> ‘holt, copse, small wood’. There are two in the Dutch province of Overijssel and another near Oberhausen in the Rhineland.","Danish: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holtan","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads so named, from the definite plural form of <i>holt</i> ‘small wood’ (see   Holt  )."]},{"name":"Holter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Selmer, Hilmar, Knute, Lars.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farmsteads in southeastern Norway, from the indefinite plural of <i>holt</i> ‘holt, small wood’ (see   Holt  ).","North German (also <b>Hölter</b>): habitational name for someone from any of several places in Westphalia called Hölt and Holt (see   Holt  ). Compare   Hoelter  ."]},{"name":"Holtman","meanings":["Dutch: variant of   Holt   + <i>man</i> ‘man’.","Americanized form of German   Holtmann  ."]},{"name":"Holtmann","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Udo, Aloys, Hans, Heinz.","North German: variant of   Holt  ."]},{"name":"Holte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Bjorg, Erik, Helmer, Hjalmer, Knute, Nels, Nordahl, Selmer, Swen, Thorvald.","North German: variant of   Holt  .","North German: habitational name from any of several places so named."]},{"name":"Hoult","meanings":["English: variant of   Holt  ."]}]},{"name":"Simon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."],"variants":[{"name":"Simen","meanings":["Usual English form of   Simeon  , borne in the New Testament by various characters: two apostles, a brother of Jesus, a Pharisee, a leper, a tanner, a sorcerer (who offered money for the gifts of the Holy Ghost, giving rise to the term <i>simony</i>), and the man who carried Jesus's cross to the Crucifixion."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":13,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Simon de Holt was born in 1302, in Holt, Worcestershire, England, his father, John de Holt III, was 28 and his mother, Alice de Castells, was 23. He married Albreda de Birmingham in 1323, in Yardley, Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1324, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1302–1324":"1302–1324","1304–1365":"1304–1365","–Male":"Surnud","1304–1334":"1304–1334","1324–1402":"1324–1402","1275–1347":"1275–1347","1279–1348":"1279–1348","1275":"12